urls.title: modelsummary: Data and Model Summaries in R by Vincent Arel-Bundock
urls.description: modelsummary is a package to summarize data and statistical models in R. It supports over one hundred types of models out-of-the-box, and allows users to report the results of those models side-by-side in a table, or in coefficient plots. It makes it easy to execute common tasks such as computing robust standard errors, adding significance stars, and manipulating coefficient and model labels. tweets.text: üßµ8/8 APIs: To access data from APIs, use the httr package. The "GET" function sends requests to APIs, and you can use the jsonlite package to convert the API response into data frames. üåâ #APIs #RStats

üßµ7/8 Web Scraping: The rvest package allows you to scrape data from websites. Use the "read_html" function to load web pages and "html_nodes" and "html_text" functions to extract specific data elements. üåê #WebScraping #RStats

üßµ6/8 SPSS, SAS, Stata: The haven package provides functions like "read_spss," "read_sas," and "read_stata" to read datasets from SPSS, SAS, and Stata software. These functions make it easy to integrate data from various statistical software. üîÄ #StatsSoftware #RStats

üßµ5/8 SQL Databases: The RMySQL, RSQLite, and RPostgreSQL packages allow you to connect to MySQL, SQLite, and PostgreSQL databases, respectively. Use "dbConnect" to establish a connection and "dbReadTable" to read the data into R. üóÑÔ∏è #SQL #RStats

üßµ4/8 JSON Files: The jsonlite package offers an easy-to-use "fromJSON" function to read JSON data into R. It converts JSON objects to data frames, making it simple to work with JSON data. üì¶ #JSON #RStats

üßµ3/8 Excel Files: The readxl package provides functions like "read_excel" for reading data from Excel files (.xls and .xlsx). Alternatively, the openxlsx package offers more features, including reading and writing Excel files. üìä #Excel #RStats

üßµ2/8 CSV Files: The "read.csv" function is a go-to for reading comma-separated values files. For improved performance and more flexibility, consider using the "read_csv" function from the readr package or the fread function from the data.table package. üìÉ #CSV #RStats

tweets.text: 5/6 üìäüë• Do you have multiple datasets that you need to combine? Use join()! This function allows you to merge datasets based on common variables. Want to combine data on a shared ID column? Use left_join(df1, df2, by = "ID") #datascience #rstats

4/6 üìäüìä group_by() allows you to group your data by one or more variables. Want to see the average value of a column for each year? Use group_by(year) %>% summarise(avg_value = mean(column)) #datascience #rstats

3/6 üìäüî¢ mutate() is a powerful function that allows you to create new columns based on existing ones. Want to calculate a new column as a ratio of two others? Use mutate(new_column = column1/column2) #datascience #rstats

2/6 üìäüîÄ Next is arrange()! This function allows you to sort your data by one or more variables. Want to see the top 10 highest values in a column? Use arrange(desc(column)) %>% slice_head(n = 10) #datascience #rstats

OK! I will start:
